{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Stale Compound exchange rate lets new deposits mint inflated shares and steal accrued yield","locations":["0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:425","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:435","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:566","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:599","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:735"],"claim":"Pool accounting prices cUSDT with `exchangeRateStored()` instead of an interest-accruing current rate. When Compound interest has accrued but the stored rate is stale, `deposit()` computes `pool` too low and mints too many shares to the new depositor. A later Compound interaction refreshes the exchange rate, letting those inflated shares redeem previously accrued yield from existing holders.","impact":"Previously accrued Compound yield can be transferred from incumbent shareholders to a new depositor, causing direct dilution and theft of vault value.","paths":["Vault assets sit in Compound long enough for `exchangeRateStored()` to lag the real exchange rate.","Attacker calls `deposit(_amount)` while `pool` is understated and receives excess shares.","Attacker or any later interaction touches Compound and refreshes the exchange rate.","Those excess shares can then be withdrawn for more USDT than the attacker contributed."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Any accounted asset donation can permanently brick deposits when total supply is zero","locations":["0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:425","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:431","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:435","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:438","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:735"],"claim":"`deposit()` decides whether to bootstrap on `pool == 0` instead of `_totalSupply == 0`. If the vault holds any asset counted by `_calcPoolValueInToken()` while `_totalSupply` is zero, the function takes the non-bootstrap path and computes `shares = _amount * 0 / pool = 0`, so the depositor receives no shares.","impact":"A dust donation before the first deposit, or after a full exit, can permanently brick the vault: later depositors transfer in funds, receive zero shares, and cannot recover the locked assets.","paths":["Attacker transfers USDT or another accounted vault asset to the contract while `_totalSupply == 0`.","A user later calls `deposit(_amount)`.","`pool` is now non-zero, so the contract skips the bootstrap branch and mints zero shares.","No shares exist to redeem the accumulated assets, leaving the vault stuck."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Public strategy entrypoints can strand idle funds in a non-provider lender and DOS withdrawals","locations":["0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:391","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:505","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:661","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:678","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:716","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:719","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:722","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:735"],"claim":"`supplyDydx`, `supplyAave`, `supplyFulcrum`, and `supplyCompound` are public and can invest whatever idle USDT is sitting in the vault, but they do not update `provider`. Pool valuation still counts those side positions, while `withdraw()` can only source liquidity through `_withdrawSome()` from the lender stored in `provider` (or from no lender at all when `provider == NONE`).","impact":"An attacker can permissionlessly strand newly deposited idle funds in a lender that `withdraw()` does not use, causing partial or full withdrawal reverts and potentially leaving a slice of vault assets inaccessible until `provider` changes and `_withdrawAll()` happens.","paths":["Users deposit and the vault keeps fresh USDT idle because deposits do not auto-invest.","Attacker calls a public `supply*` function for a lender different from `provider`, or while `provider == NONE`.","`_calcPoolValueInToken()` still includes those assets, so withdrawals are priced as if they were available.","`_withdrawSome()` only withdraws from `provider`, so once on-hand plus provider liquidity is insufficient, `withdraw()` reverts while side-position funds remain stranded."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Low","confidence":"low","title":"dYdX balances are treated as assets even if the account turns negative","locations":["0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:559","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:592","0x83f798e925bcd4017eb265844fddabb448f1707d/Contract.sol:735"],"claim":"Both `balanceDydx()` and `_balanceDydx()` ignore the `Wei.sign` field returned by dYdX and always add `bal.value` into pool accounting as though it were a positive asset.","impact":"If the configured dYdX account were ever negative, share pricing and solvency checks would overstate assets, which could lead to impossible withdrawal amounts and reverts.","paths":["The dYdX account for `dToken` reports `sign == false`.","The vault still adds `bal.value` to total pool value.","Deposits and withdrawals are then priced against overstated assets, and later redemptions may fail."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Unprotected approveToken allows infinite token approvals to potentially compromised addresses","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Not a standalone vault bug. After constructor the function generally reverts because `safeApprove` forbids non-zero-to-non-zero approvals, and any remaining approval risk depends on trusted external protocol/admin compromise rather than permissionless misuse here."},{"title":"Share calculation uses incorrect pool value leading to incorrect deposit amounts","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Using the pre-deposit pool value is the standard share-minting formula; the report's same-block unfairness claim is unsupported by this code."},{"title":"Division by zero in getPricePerFullShare when totalSupply is zero","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a view helper reverting before initialization, not a realistic protocol-level loss, theft, insolvency, or lockup issue."},{"title":"Dynamic Aave address approval in constructor can redirect approvals to attacker-controlled address","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This relies on Aave governance/admin compromise or trusted address-provider changes, not a permissionless exploit introduced by the vault itself."},{"title":"Missing return value check on Aave deposit","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The declared Aave interface returns no value. A failed deposit would revert rather than silently return false, so there is no unchecked-return vulnerability here."},{"title":"Rounding errors in withdrawal calculations can cause user fund loss","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The `add(1)` intentionally over-redeems by at most dust to satisfy the requested withdrawal; it does not by itself create realistic protocol-level loss."},{"title":"Recommend function uses external call that can be manipulated in single transaction","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Too speculative as written. The report does not establish how the APR source is derived or that it is flash-loan manipulable in a way that creates concrete vault loss."},{"title":"Missing event emissions for critical ownership functions","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Operational transparency issue only; not a reportable protocol-level vulnerability under the requested impact standard."},{"title":"Inconsistent balanceOf implementations may cause confusion","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Integration ergonomics issue, not a security vulnerability."}]}
